⎩388⎭
⎩389⎭
⎩390⎭
  subr (literal) {⎩391⎭
      ⌈⎩392⎭
   Inside definitions only, pushes compiled literal to stack ⎩393⎭
⎩394⎭
       Certain Forth words are only applicable inside compiled sequences of subroutines ⎩395⎭
       Literals are handled in different ways when interpreted when in the REPL vs⎩396⎭
       compiled into sequences of subrs ⎩397⎭
       In the REPL, when we encounter a literal, we simply push it onto the stack ⎩398⎭
       In the compiler, though, we have to create an instruction that pushes ⎩399⎭
	 the literal onto the stack. ⎩400⎭
	 Compiled code doesn't do what the REPL does, we have to hard-wire and ⎩401⎭
	 bake in code that pushes the literal when the time comes to run the sequence. ⎩402⎭
⎩403⎭
       This word - "(literal)" - is a simple case and one could actually type this ⎩404⎭
	 instruction into the REPL, but, that would be redundant.  Other kinds of words, ⎩405⎭
	 e.g. some control-flow words, tend to be messier and the code below only handles ⎩406⎭
	 the compiled aspects and ignores the REPL aspects ⎩407⎭
⎩408⎭
       "IP" is the current word index in a sequence of words being compiled. ⎩409⎭
  ⌉⎩410⎭
      defsynonym lit ≡ State.RAM [State.IP]⎩411⎭
      %push (lit)⎩412⎭
      State.IP ⇐ State.IP + 1 ⌈ move past this item (the literal) - we're done with it ⌉⎩413⎭
  }⎩414⎭
⎩415⎭
  subr branch {⎩416⎭
      ⌈ This instruction appears only inside subroutine sequences, jump to address in next cell ⌉⎩417⎭
      ⌈ This instruction is inserted into a subr sequence when compiling control-flow words, like "else" see below) ⌉⎩418⎭
      State.IP ⇐ State.RAM [State.IP]⎩419⎭
      ⌈ normally, we just execute an instruction then move the IP sequentially forward by 1 unit, i.e. IP ⇐ IP + 1 ⌉⎩420⎭
      ⌈   in this case, though, we explicitly change the IP to some other value and don't just increment it ⌉⎩421⎭
  }⎩422⎭
⎩423⎭
  subr 0branch {⎩424⎭
      ⌈ This instruction appears only inside subroutine sequences, jump on false to address in next cell ⌉⎩425⎭
      deftemp test ⇐ %toboolean (%pop)⎩426⎭
      if (test) {⎩427⎭
	  State.IP ⇐ State.IP + 1⎩428⎭
      } else {⎩429⎭
	 State.IP ⇐ State.RAM [State.IP]⎩430⎭
      }⎩431⎭
  }⎩432⎭
⎩433⎭
⎩434⎭
  ⌈ "immediate" words are fully operational even when in compile mode. Some (not all) of these words are meant to⎩435⎭
      work /only/ in compile mode. At the REPL prompt ("interpret" mode), they produce unwanted results.⎩436⎭
    immediate words: xif, xelse, xthen, xquote, xcomment, xsemi⎩437⎭
    immediate words that only have meaning in compile mode: xif, xelse, xthen, xsemi⎩438⎭
  ⌉⎩439⎭
⎩440⎭
⎩441⎭
  ⌈ IF, ELSE and THEN are "immediate" words - they should only be used inside of ":" (colon compiler) ⌉⎩442⎭
⎩443⎭
  ⌈ see diagram compiling-IF-THEN.drawio.png ⌉⎩444⎭
  subr %immediate ❲if❳ { ⎩445⎭
      ⌈ This instruction appears only inside subroutine sequences, ( f -- ) compile if test and branchFalse ⌉ ⎩446⎭
      ⌈ Step. 1: generate conditional branch to yet-unknown target1 ⌉ ⎩447⎭
      deftemp branchFalseAddress ⇐ λ_find ("0branch")⎩448⎭
      %ram+ (branchFalseAddress) ⌈ insert branch-if-false opcode (word) ⌉ ⎩449⎭
      %rpush (%RAMnext) ⌈ target1 onto r-stack as memo for later fixup ⌉ ⎩450⎭
      defsynonym target1 ≡ -1 ⎩451⎭
      %ram+ (target1) ⌈ branch target will be fixed up later ⌉ ⎩452⎭
      ⌈ Step. 2: generate code for true branch - return to compiler which will compile the following words ⌉ ⎩453⎭
      ⌈ THEN or ELSE will do the fixup of target1 ⌉ ⎩454⎭
  }⎩455⎭
⎩456⎭
  ⌈ see diagram compiling-IF-ELSE-THEN.drawio.png ⌉⎩457⎭
  subr %immediate ❲else❳ {⎩458⎭
      ⌈ Step. 1: fixup target1 from IF-true, retrieving memo from R-stack ⌉⎩459⎭
      deftemp target1 ⇐ %rpop⎩460⎭
      State.RAM [target1] ⇐ %RAMnext⎩461⎭
      ⌈ Step. 2: generate unconditional branch for preceding IF, creating new memo for target2 on R-stack ⌉⎩462⎭
      deftemp brAddress ⇐ λ_find ("branch")⎩463⎭
      %rpush (%RAMnext) ⌈ target2 address on R-stack as memo for later fixup ⌉⎩464⎭
      defsynonym target2 ≡ -1⎩465⎭
      %ram+ (target2) ⌈ branch target will be fixed up later ⌉⎩466⎭
      ⌈ Step. 3: generate code for false branch - return to compiler which will compile the following words ⌉⎩467⎭
      ⌈ THEN will do the fixup of target2 ⌉⎩468⎭
  }⎩469⎭
⎩470⎭
  ⌈ see diagrams compiling-IF-THEN.drawio.png and compiling-IF-ELSE-THEN.drawio.png ⌉⎩471⎭
  subr %immediate ❲then❳ {⎩472⎭
      ⌈ Step. 1: fixup target (from IF or from ELSE, above), retrieving memo from R-stack ⌉⎩473⎭
      deftemp target ⇐ %rpop⎩474⎭
      State.RAM [target] ⇐ %RAMnext⎩475⎭
  }⎩476⎭
⎩477⎭
  subr (do) {⎩478⎭
      ⌈ ( limit index --) Puts limit and index on return stack. ⌉⎩479⎭
      @swap⎩480⎭
      deftemp index ⇐ %pop⎩481⎭
      deftemp limit ⇐ %pop⎩482⎭
      %rpush (index)⎩483⎭
      %rpush (limit)⎩484⎭
  }⎩485⎭
⎩486⎭
  subr %immediate ❲do❳ {⎩487⎭
      ⌈ (  limit index --) Begin counted loop. ⌉⎩488⎭
      %ram+(λ_find("(do)"))  ⌈ Push do loop handler. ⌉⎩489⎭
      %rpush(%RAMnext)           ⌈ Push address to jump back to. ⌉⎩490⎭
  }⎩491⎭
⎩492⎭
  subr (loop) {⎩493⎭
      ⌈ (  -- f) Determine if loop is done. ⌉⎩494⎭
      deftemp index ⇐ %rpop⎩495⎭
      deftemp limit ⇐ %rpop⎩496⎭
      defsynonym cond ≡ (index >= limit)⎩497⎭
      %push (cond)⎩498⎭
      if (cond) { ⌈ clean up rstack if index >= limit ⌉⎩499⎭
	  %rpop⎩500⎭
	  %rpop⎩501⎭
      }  ⎩502⎭
  }⎩503⎭
⎩504⎭
  subr %immediate +loop {⎩505⎭
      ⌈ ( --) Close counted loop. ⌉⎩506⎭
      %ram+(λ_find("(loop)"))   ⌈ Compile in loop test. ⌉⎩507⎭
      %ram+(λ_find("0branch"))  ⌈ Compile in branch check. ⌉⎩508⎭
      %ram+(%rpop)           ⌈ Address to jump back to. ⌉⎩509⎭
  }⎩510⎭
⎩511⎭
  subr %immediate ❲loop❳ {⎩512⎭
      ⌈ (  --) Close counted loop. ⌉⎩513⎭
      %push (1)⎩514⎭
      @literalize                  ⌈ Default loop increment for x_loop. ⌉⎩515⎭
      %ram+(λ_find("(loop)"))   ⌈ Compile in loop test. ⌉⎩516⎭
      %ram+(λ_find("0branch"))  ⌈ Compile in branch check. ⌉⎩517⎭
      %ram+(%rpop)           ⌈ Address to jump back to. ⌉⎩518⎭
  }⎩519⎭
⎩520⎭
  subr %immediate ❲begin❳ {⎩521⎭
      %rpush (%RAMnext)  ⌈ ( --) Start indefinite loop. ⌉⎩522⎭
  }⎩523⎭
⎩524⎭
  subr %immediate ❲until❳ {⎩525⎭
      ⌈ (  f --) Close indefinite loop with test. ⌉⎩526⎭
      %ram+(λ_find("0branch"))  ⌈ Expects result of test on stack. ⌉⎩527⎭
      %ram+(%rpop)           ⌈ Address to jump back to. ⌉⎩528⎭
  }⎩529⎭
⎩530⎭
⎩531⎭
⎩532⎭
  ⌈  "... 123 constant K ..." ⌉⎩533⎭
  ⌈  at interpretation time: 123 is on the Stack, we have consumed "constant" from BUFF, BUFF now contains "K ..." ⌉⎩534⎭
  ⌈  invoke 'word' which parses "K" and pushed it. The stack becomes [... 123 "K"] ⌉⎩535⎭
  ⌈  pop "K", pop 123, create a new word called 'K' with its PFA set to 123 and its CFA set to a subr that⎩536⎭
       gets 123 from its PFA and pushes it onto the stack ⌉⎩537⎭
  subr ❲const❳ {⎩538⎭
      ⌈  get next word - the name - from BUFF ⌉⎩539⎭
      defsynonym blank ≡ 32⎩540⎭
      %push (blank)⎩541⎭
      @word⎩542⎭
      ⌈  stack is now: ( NNNN name -- ) ⌉⎩543⎭
      deftemp name ⇐ %pop⎩544⎭
      deftemp value ⇐ %pop⎩545⎭
      defsynonym normal ≡ 0⎩546⎭
      deftemp fobj ⇐ λcode (name, normal, ↪︎doconst)⎩547⎭
      %ram+ (value)⎩548⎭
  }⎩549⎭
⎩550⎭
  subr , {⎩551⎭
      λcomma (%pop)⎩552⎭
  }⎩553⎭
⎩554⎭
  subr variable {⎩555⎭
      defsynonym blank ≡ 32⎩556⎭
      %push (blank)⎩557⎭
      @word⎩558⎭
      deftemp name ⇐ %pop⎩559⎭
      deftemp value ⇐ %pop⎩560⎭
      λfvar (name, value)    ⎩561⎭
  }⎩562⎭
⎩563⎭
  subr dump {⎩564⎭
      deftemp n ⇐ %toint (%pop)⎩565⎭
      deftemp start ⇐ %toint (%pop)⎩566⎭
      %print ("----------------------------------------------------------------")⎩567⎭
      deftemp a ⇐ start⎩568⎭
      while (a < start + (λmin (n, (λlen (State.RAM) - start)))) {⎩569⎭
	  %print (a)⎩570⎭
	  %print (": ")⎩571⎭
	  %print (State.RAM [a])⎩572⎭
	  %eol⎩573⎭
	  deftemp a ⇐ a + 1⎩574⎭
      }⎩575⎭
  }⎩576⎭
⎩577⎭
  subr ! {⎩578⎭
      deftemp b ⇐ %pop⎩579⎭
      deftemp a ⇐ %pop⎩580⎭
      State.RAM [b] ⇐ a⎩581⎭
  }⎩582⎭
⎩583⎭
  subr bye { ⌈ ( --) Leave interpreter ⌉ %quit }⎩584⎭
⎩585⎭
⎩586⎭
  subr find {⎩587⎭
      ⌈ "( name | -- (name 0)|(xt 1)|(xt -1)) Search for word name." ⌉⎩588⎭
      ⌈ 3 possible results: 1. (name 0) if not found, 2. (xt 1) if found and word is immediate, 3. (xt -1) if found and word is normal ⌉⎩589⎭
      %push (32)⎩590⎭
      @word⎩591⎭
      deftemp found ⇐ λ_find(%stop)⎩592⎭
      if (0 = found) {⎩593⎭
	  %push (0)⎩594⎭
      } else {⎩595⎭
	  %pop  ⌈ # Get rid of name on stack. ⌉⎩596⎭
	  %push(found)⎩597⎭
	  deftemp immediate ⇐ -1⎩598⎭
	  if (State.RAM[%stop - 1] & 1) { immediate ⇐ 1 }⎩599⎭
	  %push(immediate)⎩600⎭
      }⎩601⎭
  }⎩602⎭
⎩603⎭
  subr ' {⎩604⎭
      ⌈ "( name -- xt|-1) Search for execution token of word name." ⌉⎩605⎭
      %push (32)⎩606⎭
      @word⎩607⎭
      deftemp name ⇐ %pop⎩608⎭
      deftemp found ⇐ λ_find(name)⎩609⎭
      %push (found)⎩610⎭
  }⎩611⎭
⎩612⎭
  subr None {⎩613⎭
      %pushNone⎩614⎭
  }⎩615⎭
⎩616⎭
  subr words {⎩617⎭
      ⌈ print words in dictionary ⌉⎩618⎭
